06494nam a2200757Ia 9780776624426DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20172016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a9780776624426  a(DE-B1597)668120  a(OCoLC)973044126  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR3109.C3bS44 2002eb 7aLIT0150002bisacsh04a822.3/300aShakespeare and Canada :bRemembrance of Ourselves /ced. by Irena R. Makaryk, Kathryn Prince. 1aOttawa : bUniversity of Ottawa Press, c[2017] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReappraisals: Canadian Writers00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations and Figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tShakespeare and Canada: "Remembrance of Ourselves" -- t"Theatre is not a nursing home": Merchants of Venice of The Stratford Festival -- tIntercultural Performance and The Stratford Festival as Global Tourist Place: Leon Rubin's A Midsummer Night's Dream and Twelfth Night -- tStratford, Shakespeare, and J. D. Barnett -- tCounterfactual History at The Stratford Festival: Timothy Findley's Elizabeth Rex and Peter Hinton's The Swanne -- t"Who's There?": Slings & Arrows' Audience Dynamics -- tRace, National Identity, and the Hauntological Ethics of Slings & Arrows -- tPerforming "Indigenous Shakespeare" in Canada: The Tempest and The Death of a Chief -- tShakespeare, a Late Bloomer on the Quebec Stage -- tMediatic Shakespeare: McLuhan and the Bard -- tShakespeare and the "Cultural Lag" of Canadian Stratford in Alice Munro's "Tricks" -- tBeyond (or Beneath) the Folio: Neil Freeman's Shakespearean Acting Pedagogy in Context -- tRhyme and Reason: Shakespeare's Exceptional Status and Role in Canadian Education -- tThe Truth About Stories About Shakespeare . . . In Canada? -- tContributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aShakespeare in Canada is the result of a collective desire to explore the role that Shakespeare has played in Canada over the past two hundred years, but also to comprehend the way our country's culture has influenced our interpretation of his literary career and heritage. What function does Shakespeare serve in Canada today? How has he been reconfigured in different ways for particular Canadian contexts? The authors of this book attempt to answer these questions while imagining what the future might hold for William Shakespeare in Canada. Covering the Stratford Festival, the cult CBC television program Slings and Arrows, major Canadian critics such as Northrop Frye and Marshall McLuhan, the influential acting teacher Neil Freiman, the rise of Québécois and First Nation approaches to Shakespeare, and Shakespeare's place in secondary schools today, this collection reflects the diversity and energy of Shakespeare's afterlife in Canada. Collectively, the authors suggest that Shakespeare continues to offer Canadians "remembrance of ourselves." This is a refreshingly original and impressive contribution to Shakespeare studies-a considerable achievement in any work on the history of one of the central figures in the western literary canon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aTheaterzCanadaxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh1 aBrisset, Annie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavell, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColarusso, Dana M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColarusso, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischlin, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular